<HEADLINE> UK Likely to End Ban on Front-Line Roles for Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 26 (Xinhua) -- The British government is likely to
put an end to a ban on women serving in front-line army roles in
an effort to ease the recruitment crisis in the country's armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
British Defense Secretary George Robertson was quoted by the
BBC television as saying today that the Ministry of Defense will
undertake a wide-ranging review of women's role in the armed
forces to see whether to abolish the traditional barring of women
from front-line duty.
</P>
<P>
"If a woman wants to do it and is fit enough and it does not
compromise combat effectiveness, then perhaps we should look again
at modern attitudes to these things," he said.
</P>
<P>
Robertson made it clear that he had no objection in principle
to extending the women's role in the army, saying, "We've got to
make sure that the armed forces of this country are seen to be up
to date, to be modern, enlightened and fair. That's why the role
of women is so important."
</P>
<P>
"I think that as many positions should be open to as many
people as possible. What we're obliged to look at is the practical
impact of our policies," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
