<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Likely to Have New Cabinet with Old Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Valery
Pustovoitenko announced today a new cabinet will be in place when
the parliament reconvenes on August 28, but chances of seeing many
new faces in the cabinet are slim.
</P>
<P>
"The same people will remain in the same post," said Roman
Zwarycz, director of the Center for Democratic Reform, a Ukrainian
think tank. "They may just be reorganized among different
ministries again."
</P>
<P>
Thanks to vague constitutional guidelines, Ukrainian President
Leonid Kuchma and Pustovoitenko are under no time pressure to form
a new government, nor must they seek the approval of Parliament
for any governmental changes.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian constitution gives the president exclusive
authority to accept or reject nominees for ministerial posts that
are submitted by the prime minister. In addition, Pustovoitenko is
at any rate viewed as a Kuchma surrogate unlikely to disagree with
his longtime boss.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko is the first prime minister belonging to a
particular party. His colleagues in the People's Democratic Party
(PDP) acknowledged that they would take an active role in the
appointment of new ministers.
</P>
<P>
"The PDP is conscious of its participation in the formation of
a new cabinet and is ready to take responsibility for all its
representatives there," said PDP First Deputy Chairman Volodymyr
Filenko.
</P>
<P>
Controlling just 21 of the 450 seats in Parliament, the PDP is
ready to support non-PDP members to be nominated by Pustovoitenko,
added Filenko.
</P>
<P>
Recent history shows that the new government will bear a strong
likeness to its predecessors. Most officials in the current
cabinet have served in at least one of the other five governments
Ukraine has had since independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Many officials are not likely to shift position at all,
observers say.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the PDP will recommend that its members in the
present government be re-appointed, including Economy Minister
Yury Yekhanurov, National Agency for Reconstruction and
Development head Roman Shpek and Information Minister Zinovy Kulyk.
</P>
<P>
Of the other cabinet members, observers say Foreign Minister
Gennady Udovenko's position is among the most secure because he
enjoys a favorable reputation abroad and has few enemies at home.
</P>
<P>
Filenko said likely candidates for new appointments are PDP
leader Anatoly Matviyenko and fellow party member Anatoly
Tolstoukhov, who currently serves as deputy Cabinet minister and
may take Pustovoitenko's place as head of the Cabinet apparatus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
