<HEADLINE> Egypt's Oil Export Up in 1996/97 Fiscal Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's export of crude oil and oil
products reached 2.764 billion U.S. dollars in value in the past
fiscal year ending June 30, up 14 percent from a year ago, an
Arabic daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Al Ahram quoted Petroleum Minister Hamdi Al-Banbi as saying
that production has begun since last year in seven new oil fields
in the Western Desert and the Suez Gulf, as well as in five new
natural gas plants near the Mediterranean Sea and in the Nile
Delta. But he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, a member of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting
Countries and the fourth largest oil exporter in Africa, has a
proven crude reserve of 3.9 billion barrels and produces about
917,000 barrels of oil a day. It exports about half of its output.
</P>
<P>
Al-Banbi said the value of local consumption of petroleum
products and natural gas reached 10.7 billion dollars in the past
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Natural gas is now available in 76,000 homes in the capital
Cairo, 40,000 homes in Alexandria and 14,000 homes in Port Said,
both on the coast of the Mediterranean, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's production of natural gas has grown five times during
last 15 years, from 2.2 billion cubic meters in 1981 to around 13
billion in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government is reportedly planning to provide nearly 1.5
million housing units with natural gas during the coming six years.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has recently concluded nine agreements with eight
international companies which will inject 102 million dollars to
dig in 29 oil and gas fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Banbi has endorsed the timetable and plans of action to set
up three large oil projects during the ongoing fiscal year (July
1, 1997-June 30, 1998), the first year of the country's fourth
five-year plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
