<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-26 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM Returns After Consultation with Greek </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides returned home today from Athens after two-day
consultations with Greek government prior to the second round of
direct talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters upon his return, Kasoulides said he had a
"useful exchange of views" with the Greek government on specific
issues relating to the talks scheduled for August 11-16 in
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said he briefed his Greek counterpart Theodoros
Pangalos on the latest developments ahead of the forthcoming
negotiations and prior to a meeting of the island's political
leadership on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides was accompanied by Attorney General Alecos
Markides who was President Glafcos Clerides' legal advisor at the
U.N.-led first round direct talks earlier this month near New York.
</P>
<P>
"This exchange of views showed a convergence of opinion on
almost all the issues at hand," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Turkey's threats to partially integrate Cyprus'
northern areas, the Minister said Greece shared the position
the Cypriot government has adopted on the matter and agreed
with its response to the Turkish provocations.
</P>
<P>
According to reports reaching here from Athens, Greek Foreign
Minister Pangalos was quoted as saying Friday night after a
meeting with Kasoulides that the Greek government is determined
to stand by the Cypriot government using all its contacts and
work for a just and lasting settlement for the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
"We insist that this is the time to have a Cyprus solution and
we believe there must be a final end to the Turkish occupation of
part of Cyprus," Pangalos told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He also noted the start of European Union (EU) - Cyprus
accession talks early next year offers an opportunity for a
settlement of the protracted Cyprus question.
</P>
<P>
A Cyprus solution, he added, will be a significant step
towards the improvement of the climate in southeastern
Mediterranean and will promote Turkey's prospects toward Europe.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops took
over the northern third of the island in the wake of a failed
coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both NATO allies, have been at odds over
this East Mediterranean strategic island.
</P>
<P>
But the two countries' relations have been improved recently,
especially by an agreement reached in Madrid earlier this
month that they agreed to settle disputes by peaceful means
based on mutual consent and without use of force or threat
of force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
