<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Adopts Affirmative Action for Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's ruling party, Zimbabwe
African National Union-Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF) has agreed on an
affirmative action to enable more women to get top government
positions.
</P>
<P>
President Robert Mugabe today said the party had realised that
women were not fully recognised.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed within the party that we have to give women a quota
system," he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the party had not yet agreed on the percentage of the
quota system although Mugabe had suggested a 25 percent as a good
start.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe has appointed five women to the posts of Minister of
State in charge of gender, Minister of State in charge of social
affairs, Minister of State in charge of economy, Deputy Minister
of National Affairs, Employment Creation and Cooperatives, and
Deputy Minister of Home Affairs, with the first three appointed
during this week's cabinet reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one of Zimbabwe's 150 parliament members are female,
which is considered one of the highest figure in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
