<HEADLINE> China, Australia Pledge to Promote Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 26 (Xinhua) -- China and
Australia today shared the view that the deepening of their
relations not only conforms to the fundamental interests of the
two countries but is also conducive to stability and development
in the region.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting here, Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen and
his Australian counterpart Alexander Downer held that there has
been a good momentum this year in the development of the
Sino-Australian relations.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the exchange of visits at the top level has
been resumed and the development of economic and trade ties has
been smooth, a Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman told a press
briefing.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the two countries should further tap the potentials
for mutually beneficial cooperation and should establish and
develop long-lasting and stable friendship, according to spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also discussed international and regional
issues of common interest and agreed that the two countries should
further strengthen their cooperation in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Recalling their recent meeting in Hong Kong, Qian said that
about one month after its return to the motherland, Hong Kong has
maintained its prosperity and stability.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that Hong Kong will have a brighter future,"
Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Downer, who thanked the Chinese side for inviting him to attend
the ceremony marking Hong Kong's return to China, expressed his
optimism about Hong Kong's future, saying there is no reason for
people to be pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers are here to attend the ASEAN Regional Forum
(ARF) scheduled to be held tomorrow and the Post Ministerial
Conference on July 28-29.  
</P>
</TEXT>
