<HEADLINE> Pakistan PM Hopes to See Peace Restored in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif said today it was his keen desire to see restoration of
peace to Afghanistan as it would not only benefit the Afghan
people but the entire region as well.
</P>
<P>
Sharif made the remarks when addressing a gathering at Torkham,
a small town bordering Afghanistan and about 200 km northwest of
here, according to a report by the Associated Press of Pakistan
(APP).
</P>
<P>
However, the APP made no mention of the purpose of Sharif's
visit to the border town at a time when fighting between Afghan
warring factions was escalating north of Kabul, capital of
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was playing its due role in this regard and would
continue to do so in a bid to solve the problems confronting the
people there, Sharif was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Peace in Afghanistan was also vital for economic development of
all the countries in the region, he said, adding that it was
incumbent upon Pakistan to fulfill its responsibility in these
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said Pakistan has been striving to bring all the rival
factions in Afghanistan to the negotiating table in efforts to
seek lasting peace in the war-ravaged country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
