<HEADLINE> Grenade Explosion Kills Three in Tehran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Three people of a family were
killed and another three injured as a hand grenade exploded in a
house in Vali-Asre township in southern Tehran, a local evening
paper reported here today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian paper Kayhan reported that Qodrat Farangi, the
47-year-old father, Habibeh Javadi, the 47-year-old mother and
their 6-year-old daughter, Layla, were killed as the hand grenade
exploded last Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Qodrat Farangi, a municipal worker, had apparently found the
hand grenade in the garbage and was tampering with it on his
rooftop on the night of the explosion, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Farangi's three other daughters, aged 20, 17 and 14
respectively, sustained severe injuries and have been
hospitalized, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Opposition Mandates Body for Talks With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan opposition parties today
mandated the National Convention Executive Council (NCEC) to
negociate with the ruling party on constitutional reforms, the
Kenyan Television Network (KTN) reported.
</P>
<P>
The ruling Kenya African National Union (KANU) "has no rights
to suggest fool to represent the opposition during the talks,"
said official opposition leader Kijana Wamalwa at a rally of some
5,000 people held in Kenya's main port city Mombasa.
</P>
<P>
The rally was also attended by leaders from other main
opposition parties, the Democratic Party, National Development
Party, Social Democratic Party and FORD-Asili.
</P>
<P>
The leaders, who advocated for minimum constitutional reforms
since the beginning of this year, now calls for the "total"
reforms before the forthcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
The government issued a permit to the Mombasa rally, avoiding
a potential violent confrontation between the opposition
supporters and the government.
</P>
<P>
While the meeting was held in Mombasa, three detachments of
riot police were sent to patrol the Indian Ocean port city which
is at the heart of Kenyan's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen people were killed on July 7 around the country in
running battles between the riot police and demonstrators in
kenya's worst civil unrest for seven years.
</P>
<P>
President Daniel arap Moi said on July 16 that permits for
rallies would automatically be granted except in exceptional
cases.
</P>
<P>
The United States Friday welcomed a government plan for talks
with the opposition and for political reforms before general
elections, saying it is essential that pre-election rallies and
other events remained peaceful.
</P>
<P>
As many as 22 foreign embassies and high commissions in Kenya
sent a letter to President Moi a few days ago, urging him to
pursue dialogue with the opposition to avoid more political
violence, according to the local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
Adding to pressure on the Moi government, the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) has given the government one week to
demonstrate strong management and make commitments of
accountability or lose a large annual loan.
</P>
<P>
The IMF gave Kenya a three-year loan package worth 205 million
U.S. Dollars in April last year, but regular payments could be
made on the condition that Kenya met promises on reform issues.
</P>
<P>
From May to July, violence has been escalating when the
opposition repeatedly tried to hold rallies without governmental
permit in a bid to press for constitutional reforms before the
general elections. All the rallies were broken up by the police.
</P>
<P>
Under the current constitution, any candidate, if he wins no
less than 25 percent of votes respectively in five of the eight
provinces of Kenya, he can be qualified as a legal president.
</P>
<P>
The opposition leaders urged to change the clause, demanding
the future president get more than 50 percent of the total votes
nationwide. This has always been refused by Moi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
