<HEADLINE> Tanzanian President Leaves for Democratic Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa left here today for the Democratic Republic of
Congo (formerly Zaire) for a one-day visit during which he will
hold talks with President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and
International Co-operation said that the talks between Mkapa and
Kabila will focus on future political and bilateral ties between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzaanian president, accompanied by Minister for Foreign
Affairs and International Co-operation Jakaya Kikwete and other
senior officials, was expected to make a stop-over in Kigali,
Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
During his brief stop in Kigali, Mkapa planned to hold
discussions with President Pasteur Bizimungu.
</P>
<P>
This is President Mkapa's first visit to Kinshasa since Kabila
swept to power after a seven-month war which ousted former
Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, other issues to dominate the talks
include the speedy return of 100,000 Congoless refugees who fled
into Tanzania during the political turmoil in former Zaire.
</P>
</TEXT>
