<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Start State Television Broadcasting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye today asked the Tanzania Broadcasting Commission
to technically assist the government in starting the state
television in phases during this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the commission's new board in Dodoma, central
Tanzania, Sumaye said that state television would start by
beaming signals in Dar es Salaam and coastal regions and later
expand nationwide.
</P>
<P>
"Since the government's coffers are thin, starting up on a
national approach will still be difficult and might take longer.
Therefore, the best strategy should be to begin in phases," said
the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government banked on the commission because
it had a pool of experts who could best advise the government on
the setting up of the state television.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sumaye commended the work of the media in the
country but challenged them to develop journalism, saying it is
high time for journalists to report positive events when the
county is making reforms economically and politically.
</P>
<P>
He also urged private televisions in the country to have more
local programs for the benefit of viewers.
</P>
<P>
He suggested that private radio stations in Tanzania broadcast
their news bulletins at different time to ensure the effective
dissemination of news in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
