<HEADLINE> Nigerians Warned Against Misleading by Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- A state military administrator has
adviced Nigerians not to be misled into believing that the unity
of Nigeria could be achieved by international mischief makers,
local media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The foreign media have been spreading information about issues
they do not understand with an intent to destabilize the country,
said Rivers State Administrator Musa Shehu.
</P>
<P>
They also intended to derail the on-going transition to civil
rule in the country, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has made some amendment to its transition programs by
shifting state governorship and assembly election from the second
half of this year to next year.
</P>
<P>
According to the new timetable, elections of state governors
and president will be held together.
</P>
<P>
The change in the timetable, which is meant to avoid possible
trouble between civilian state governors and the military head of
state, has led to speculation whether the military will hand over
power to the civilian government in October,1998 as it announced.
</P>
<P>
Shehu, however, expressed his confidence in the sincerity of
Nigerian President Sani Abacha in ensuring a successful
implementation of the program to usher in a democratically
elected government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
