<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Foreign Debts Drop to 6 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Hashemi
Rafsanjani announced today that Iran's foreign debts have dropped
to 6 billion U.S. dollars from the record of 33 billion dollars
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing president made the statement while addressing a
group of bank managers. He said that the reduction of foreign
debt "indicates the manufacturing capability of the country."
</P>
<P>
However, the amount of Iran's foreign debt announced by
Rafsanjani surprised many as the recent official figures put
Iran's debt at over 18 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the official news agency IRNA,
the 64-year-old president appreciated the basic role played by
Iranian banks in financing reconstruction projects.
</P>
<P>
He said that the progress made by the country today was
a result of current reconstruction programs.
</P>
<P>
He said the banks have taken part in the infrastructural
investments, adopted measures to attract public confidence and
deposits and managed to transform the negative trends in
financial sector to positive.
</P>
<P>
"The economic stability in Iran has served to neutralize
the political pressures being exerted on Iran and the reduction
in dependence upon foreign countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the anti-Iran policy of the United States, he
said, the failure of the U.S. Congress plan to exert pressure on
Iran indicated the economic strength of the country.
</P>
<P>
Finance and Economic Minister Morteza Mohammad Khan said at
the meeting that Iran's banking deposits hit 100,000 billion
Rials (about 33 billion dollars) during the 12-month period
starting March 21, 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said that some 60,000 billion Rials (about 20 billion
dollars) were extended in banking loans to Iranians.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Khan said the inflation was brought down to below
16 percent last year from 43 percent in the preceding year.
However, unofficial estimates have put Iran's inflation as high
as 50 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
