<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Warns Against Worsening Peace Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today warned the peace process could slide into abyss if
Israel's settlement policy continues unbridled.
</P>
<P>
Moussa sounded the alarm in the wake of talks between President
Hosni Mubarak and Palestinian National Authority President Yasser
Arafat in the Mediterranean port city of Alexandria.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Mubarak summit came two days after Israel's
Jerusalem municipality gave green light to the building of a
Jewish settler enclave in the 11,000-strong Arab neighborhood of
Ras el Amud in the heart of East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that the planned Jewish enclave and other ongoing
Israeli settlement activities would pull down the real bases upon
which the peace process can continue.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the confiscation of Palestinian lands and rights
will be inevitable once Israel goes ahead with the new settlement
in the Palestinian village.
</P>
<P>
"All should rally to stop and put a limit to the Israeli
settlement policy in order to forestall any further deterioration of
the already-grave situation, otherwise it will negatively reflect
on the peace tracks and the whole region as well," he added.
</P>
<P>
Combined mediation efforts so far have failed to galvanize the
crippled Palestinian-Israeli peace talks since March as Israel
began building thousands of homes for Jewish settlers in Har Homa
in East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians want as their future
capital.
</P>
<P>
Moussa added that the main points that require profound
discussions are the "necessity of forging a solution to the
economic embargo clamped on the Palestinians, the construction of
settlements in Palestinian territories and the stalemate
witnessed on the Palestinian-Israeli track as well as Israeli
redeployment.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt's stance is clear-cut and recognizes the exigency of
salvaging the peace process, a momentous and principal drive where
concentration on subsidiary matters are not enough," said the
Egyptian top diplomat.
</P>
<P>
Moussa also dismissed a European proposal for a four-power
summit among Mubarak, Arafat, Jordan's King Hussein and Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the convocation of any summit must be based on
progress in the peace process and on results to be achieved in
favor of the peace drive.
</P>
<P>
"Any summit is not an end in itself to give a space of time to
Israel to carry on with its settlement activities as was the case
in many occasions before," he said, adding that Egypt insists on
the importance of realizing an equitable peace and giving every
party its own rights.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few days, Arafat held talks with Israeli
opposition Labor Party leader Ehud Barak, Foreign Minister David
Levy and a number of European officials in a bid to rescue the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
But according to Moussa, Arafat is "extremely pessimistic"
about further talks between PNA Minister of Planning and
International Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath and Levy, whom the
Palestinian leader personally met in Brussels Wednesday, in the
highest-level contact between the two sides in the five months
since crisis began. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
