<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Exports of Services on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's exports of
commercial services grew by an average of 9.1 percent annually
between 1990 and 1996, the Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB)
said today.
</P>
<P>
It said that last year, Singapore's exports of commercial
services amounted to 47 billion Singapore dollars (about 32.4
billion US dollars), representing about 54 percent of non-oil
domestic exports.
</P>
<P>
Shipment, which included freight and insurance related to the
movements of goods, and other services, which included business
and professional services, accounted for about 77 percent of total
services exports, while travel services accounted for the
remaining 23 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
The World Trade Organization said Singapore improved its
ranking as a commercial services exporter from 18th place in 1985
to 12th place in 1995, the TDB noted.
</P>
<P>
It said that a comparison with three other Newly Industrialized
Economies (NIEs), namely, South Korea, Hong Kong, and Taiwan,
shows that Singapore's share achieved in 1995 for services exports
was the second highest, behind Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
For growth prospects of the services sector, the TDB said that
while competition from other services exporters will intensify, an
increase in global demand for services is also anticipated.
</P>
<P>
Global demand for services is expected to continue to grow by
healthy rates, it said, noting that global exports of services
expanded by 12 percent during the 1985-95 period compared to ten
percent annum attained for the exports of goods.
</P>
<P>
The TDB said that it plans to devote more resources to develop
the full potential of Singapore's services exports, but added that
this would not be at the expense of efforts to promote trade in
goods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
