<HEADLINE> Azeri President to Pay First Official Visit to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Azeri President Haydar Aliyev said
today that he would discuss the conflict between Azerbaijan and
Armenia with U.S. President Bill Clinton upon the departure for
his first official visit to the United States since Azerbaijan
gained independence from the former Soviet Union in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Aliyev also said that he would seek removal of U.S. legislation
barring government aid for Azerbaijan until his country resumes
trade ties with Armenia, Inter-fax News Agency reported from the
Azeri capital of Baku.
</P>
<P>
During the week-long visit, Aliyev will sign three pacts on
the Azeri-U.S.cooperation in developing Azerbaijan's oil reserves, in
which the United States will invest 10 billion U.S. dollars, half
of the foreign investment in energy development in Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijan, a Central Asian country located by the Caspian Sea,
is rich in oil and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The United States has been advocating in the recent months
solving the conflict between Azerbaijan and Armenia over
Nagorno-Karabakh, an enclave inside Azerbaijan which is inhabited
mainly by Armenians.
</P>
<P>
"Conflict resolution must be Job One for U.S. policy in the
(Central Asian) region: it is both the prerequisite for, and an
accompaniment to , energy development," said Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
A 1994 ceasefire ended the territorial dispute, which began
in the late 1980s with the breaking away of Nagorno-Karabakh. But
a political settlement to the conflict, which had claimed tens of
thousands of life, remains a question. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
