<HEADLINE> Libel Case Against Mubarak's Sons Adjourned Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A Cairo court today again adjourned
until September 7 hearings into a libel suit filed by Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak's sons against a Saudi magazine, the
Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Three Egyptians and three Saudis, including the magazine owner,
were charged on July 12 with publishing a slanderous story about
the sons' shading business dealings.
</P>
<P>
Ashraq Al Awsat daily, part of the Saudi publishing group of
the same name, published on May 27 an advertisement for its sister
weekly Al Jadida containing an article implicating Mubarak's sons
in illegal business dealings.
</P>
<P>
The six are facing sentences of a maximum of three years in
prison and a fine if convicted of "defamation and attacking
(Mubarak) family honor."
</P>
<P>
The same court agreed to postpone the case until today during
its first hearing a week ago at the request of the defense
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers said the defendants had admitted wrongdoing and
asked for the "leniency and forgiveness" of Mubarak's sons, saying
that they only meant to promote the nascent magzine.
</P>
<P>
Only Sayed Abdel-Atti, author of the article, lives in Egypt
while the others are in London and Saudi Arabia and will be tried
in absentia, prosecution sources said.
</P>
<P>
But the advertised article never appeared in the magazine as it
was taken out in a last minute decision in response to the
Egyptian protest and the weekly's two editors were sacked.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak's two sons, who are both prominent members of Egyptian
business groups, said the ad "included lies defaming their
characters and the reputation of their family." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
