<HEADLINE> Southwest China Province Encourages Private Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Sichuan Province in southwest
China has worked out policies that encourage development in the
private sector to give it a bigger role in economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has put no limit on the private
sector's development speed, scale, managerial system, and form of
operations, according to the latest edition of China Business
Times.
</P>
<P>
The goverment will treat technology-intensive private
enterprises the same as state-owned ones in research projects and
applying for loans. And private businesses that do well will be
permitted to make use of idle assets of small and medium-sized
state enterprises through shares, acquisitions, leases, buyouts,
or contracts.
</P>
<P>
The province has taken an unprecedented step in putting a
deputy governor in charge of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The private economy has been developing steadily since China
adopted its reforms and opening-up policy in the late 1970s, and
has provided a growing number of job opportunities, especially for
laid-off workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
