<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Praises Sino-Indian Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese
Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen today evaluated
highly the development of relations between China and India.
</P>
<P>
Meeting Indian Finance Minister P. Chidambaram here, Qian noted
that the state visit made to India by Chinese President Jiang
Zemin at the end of last year was of great significance, a Chinese
Foreign Ministry spokesman told reporters tonight.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy to see that senior leaders of China and India
have paid visits to each other and the economic and trade
relations between the two countries have been continuously growing
and the two nations support each other in international affairs,"
Qian was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Qian also pointed out that the two countries share many things
in common in their efforts to promote their respective countries'
development and improve their people's living standards.
</P>
<P>
Mutual understanding and trust have been increasing between
China and India, he said, adding that this is conducive to smooth
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We attach importance to Sino-Indian relations and friendship
and appreciate India's effort to improve relations, live
peacefully and seek common development with other countries on the
South Asian Subcontinent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian said there exist many disputes and conflicts in the world
today and he called for solving international and regional
disputes and problems through peaceful negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Chidambaram agreed with Qian's views concerning the two
countries' relationship and expressed his government's
satisfaction with the development of the ties, according to the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister pointed out that economic and trade
cooperation between the two countries has also been expanding in
recent years and cooperation in industrial, aviation and other
fields has also made progress.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister pledged to continue his effort to promote
the friendship and relations between India and China, including
boosting economic and trade ties, establishing joint ventures and
increasing personnel exchange.
</P>
<P>
He agreed with Qian that differences between countries should
be solved through peaceful negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his country's readiness to strengthen
cooperation with China in multilateral forums and projects.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers are here to attend the ASEAN Regional Forum
and Post Ministerial Conference scheduled for July 27-29.
</P>
</TEXT>
