<HEADLINE> Most Arab Countries Achieve Real Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A total of 13 Arab countries
out of the 22-member Arab League recorded a rise in their annual
growth rates of 4 to 7 percent in 1996, an economic report said
today.
</P>
<P>
An annual report published by the Kuwait-based Arab
Corporation for Investment Guarantee, said countries achieved
growth rates were Mauritania by 7 percent, Tunisia 6.9
percent, Jordan 5.2 percent, Egypt 4.9 percent, Sudan 4.7
percent, Yemen 4.5 percent and Algeria 4.4 percent,
</P>
<P>
Six other countries including Lebanon, Morocco and four oil
exporting Gulf Arab countries such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Oman and the United Arab Emirates achieved a growth rate of
4 percent each, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, Palestine recorded a minus 3 percent growth rate, the
report pointed out.
</P>
<P>
It said that compared with 1995, last year witnessed remarkable
progress as Morocco moved from minus 6.5 percent to 4 percent while
Tunisia's jumped from 2.4 percent to 6.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
As for inflation, the report said that most Arab countries
with records available kept their inflation rates within
acceptable limits except Syria with 20 percent, Algeria with
19 percent, Yemen with 28 percent and Sudan with 136
percent.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Sudan were the most attractive for investment in
the Arab world in 1996, receiving nearly 60 percent of the
total direct capital in the region.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996, the Egyptian government has embarked on an
ambitious privatization program with reforms seen as crucial to
attract direct foreign investment and to put the country on the
map as a "tiger" economy similar to emerging Asian markets,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
There is a remarkable improvement in the investment climate
in the Arab world, especially in member countries which are carrying
out reforms, economists said.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf oil-exporting countries had benefited lot from the
higher oil prices last year due to an increase of demand
in the world oil market.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries were also seen making great efforts to
strengthen their capital markets with an aim to increase the
total issues from the current 130 billion U.S. dollars to
500 billion dollars by the turn of the century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
