<HEADLINE> Journalists Detained in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Security officials in Freetown
have detained four newsmen after the publishing office of a
biweekly newspaper, "Independent Unity Now", was raided, a
spokesman for the military junta said today.
</P>
<P>
Frank Kposowa, whose newspaper has been critical of the
military junta which staged a coup in May to topple the
legitimate government, fled Saturday under pressure from the
military authorities.
</P>
<P>
Kposowa is also head of the Sierra Leone Association of
Journalists.
</P>
<P>
He was wanted by the junta because the latest issue of his
paper called for an immediate departure of the ruling armed
forces and criticized the country's chief justice for swearing in
military leader Johnny Paul Koroma as head of State.
</P>
<P>
Two of the four people detained are journalists working for
the Sierra Leone News Agency, who were at the office when it was
raided, an eyewitness said.
</P>
<P>
The other two are workers at the newspaper's office.
</P>
<P>
Three weeks ago, seven people, including three journalists
were arrested by the police who raided the office of another
independent newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, junta leader Johnny Paul Koroma sent a message to
congratulate Charles Taylor upon his victory in Liberia's polls
at the week end.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said the message to Taylor is significant
as Liberia will play a key role in sanctions, if any, imposed
against Sierra Leone over the current political impasse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
