<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Oil Reserves Remain Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The world's proved oil reserves
were estimated at 1036.9 billion barrels by the end of 1996,
virtually unchanged compared with that of 1989.
</P>
<P>
According to a world energy report published here today, of the
total proven oil reserves, members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) hold 788.6 billion barrels,
or 76 percent, while non-OPEC countries have 248.3 billion
barrels, or 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Statistical Review of World Energy 1997 said the world's
proved oil reserves continue to be dominated by the Middle East,
which holds 65 percent of the total, with Saudi Arabia possessing
the largest share of 261.5 billion barrels, or 25 percent, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
It also said that new discoveries in oil exploration did not
change the total oil reserves because of increased oil production
in the world.
</P>
<P>
The world's total oil production in 1996 stood at 3361.6
million tonnes (about 24.5 billion barrels) while new discoveries
kept at the same level, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
