<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Children's Malnutrition Still Grave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is one of the few countries
in southern Africa that have failed to alleviate the situation in
child malnutrition, according to a report released by the
government and the United Nations system in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia News Agency today quoted the report issued here as
saying that the malnutrition levels have remained high over the
past two decades with no signs of improvements.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, 40 percent of Zambian children are
stunted as a result of chronic malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
It says the predominance of maize as children's diet is one of
the factors for the widespread diseases among them, because the
high fiber content of maize meal impairs children's ability to
absorb adequate amounts of other nutrients essential for growth.
</P>
<P>
Poverty, inadequate child care and inadequate access to health
services are also causes of the situation, says the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
