<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Unable to Repay Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is unable to repay its
foreign debts totaling about seven billion U.S. Dollars because
of its declining export earnings, an official said.
</P>
<P>
the Zambia News Agency today quoted a report released by
Finance Minister Ronald Penza as saying that Zambia's export
earnings which depend mostly on copper have been declining and
that the country is earning very little in terms of exports.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Zambia's total debt is more than five
times its total export earnings, making it one of the world's
most indebted countries.
</P>
<P>
The report stresses the need for further debt relief from
Zambia's creditors like the International Monetary Fund and the
World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Although donors' aid to Zambia has been fairly high in recent
years, it complained that most of it has been used in servicing
the external debts.
</P>
<P>
This has left the government with little to invest in its
economic recovery programs, thereby hindering its national
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
