<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's DMK Not to Withdraw From Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam
(DMK), an important constituent of India's ruling United Front,
today decided that it would not pull out from the coalition
government headed by Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral, Press
Trust of India reported.
</P>
<P>
Annoyed by the recent crisis within the United Front triggered
by the split of the Janata Dal, Tamil Nadu Chief Minister and DMK
chief M. Karunanidhi on July 14 threatened to withdraw his party's
four ministers from the Gujral government if the front could not
set its house in order by July 27.
</P>
<P>
Former Janata Dal president Laloo Prasad Yadav floated a new
party of Rashtriya Janata Dal (RJD) on July 5 after a fierce power
struggle with his party colleagues including former prime minister
H.D. Deve Gowda and the then Janata Dal working president Sharad
Yadav.
</P>
<P>
Though Prasad Yadav expressed support for the Gujral government
and favored the stay of his new party in the United Front, Gowda,
along with others, has been strongly opposing the entry of RJD
into the front.
</P>
<P>
Prasad Yadav's opponents also pressed Gujral to remove three
ministers from his government who were nominated by Prasad Yadav
before.
</P>
<P>
The disputes over the fate of the RJD and the three ministers
have undermined the unity of the 13-party United Front, posing a
serious threat to the stability of the three-month-old government
headed by Gujral.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on July 14, Karunanidhi, who favored the
stay of the RJD in the front and the continuance of the three
ministers loyal to Prasad Yadav, accused some United Front leaders
of forming a coterie within the front and using the front to
settle their personal scores.
</P>
<P>
Vowing to control the suicidal tendencies within the front,
Karunanidhi warned that the DMK would take a final decision on its
withdrawal from the United Front government on July 27 if and only
if the front could not set its house in order before that date.
</P>
<P>
At a crucial meeting held on July 25, the United Front leaders
agreed to keep out of the RJD but leave the fate of the three
ministers loyal to Prasad Yadav to the discretion of Prime
Minister Gujral who is known to favor the continuance of the
ministers in his government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting of DMK leaders in
Chennai, capital of Tamil Nadu, today, Karunanidhi announced that
his party had decided not pull out from the United Front
government.
</P>
<P>
He said that his statement threatened to pull out from the
government had brought about the "desired result" in the
functioning of the United Front and also cohesiveness in the
front.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
