<HEADLINE> Cross-Strait Railway Project for South China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A major railway project linking
Hainan, China's southernmost island province, with the mainland
will begin before the end of the year, according to Wu Changyuan,
deputy governor of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
The railway will go from Zhanjiang City in Guangdong province,
cross the Qiongzhou Straits by ferry to Haikou, the provincial
capital, then on to Changjiang County.
</P>
<P>
The ferry boat is designed to carry 4,600 tons at a speed of no
less than 15 knots. Plans are for it to carry eight million tons
annually by 2005 and 10.2 million tons by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The project also calls for connecting up with existing railway
lines on Hainan and the building of some new lines.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is expected to cost 4.5 billion yuan and to
become operational within 3 years, got approval from the State
Council in 1992. A firm has been set up by the two provincial
governments and the Ministry of Railways to oversee the project.
</P>
<P>
The railway is significant for the development of Hainan
because it will link the island to the mainland's railway network.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, the bulk of the goods moved between the
island province and the mainland will depend on railways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
