<HEADLINE> Chinese Paddlers Keep Unbeaten at China Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese paddlers kept clean sheet
on the second day of the Tianjin stop in the Chinese international
table tennis challenge tournament here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, world no. 5 Chinese veteran Wang Tao met tough
challenge from his Russian counterpart Dmitry Mazunov and had to
struggled five sets to down his world no. 26 rival 3-2.
</P>
<P>
Lagging behind 0-2, Mazunov pulled back 2-all against Wang, who
has not recovered completely from the injury.
</P>
<P>
The experienced Wang finally grasped the serve chance to edged
his opponent after the two played to a 13-13 tie in the rubber.
Wang outplayed Mazunov 21-19, 21-14, 17-21, 14-21, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
Mazunov was disappointed after the match, which he thought he
could have won.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't take the good chance, and it seems that I really have
little chance to beat him again." said Mazunov.
</P>
<P>
In another match of the day, Cheng Hongxia of China easily beat
Swedish Pernilla Pettersson 21-12, 21-18, 21-11.
</P>
<P>
Pettersson, the world no. 47, went down to China's Wang Nan 0-3
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Tianjin competiton was the second stop of the China's
challenge. The first stop was held last week in Changshu, Jiangsu
Province while the next stop is to be played next week in Chengdu,
capital of northwest China's Sichuan province. 
</P>
