<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Forum Important for Regional Security , Says Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Fourth
Regional Forum (ARF) of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) has grown into "an important forum for multilateral
security dialogue and cooperation" in the region, the ARF chairman
said today.
</P>
<P>
The ARF "has played a positive role in enhancing mutual
understanding and trust, promoting greater transparency as well as
strengthening the commitment among participants to maintain peace
and stability in the region," Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, also
Malaysia's Foreign Minister, said in a statement at the end of the
one-day session here.
</P>
<P>
"The overall security environment in the Asia-Pacific region
continues to improve." "Notwithstanding the existence of certain
challenges, the area remains stable and peaceful," the statement
added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministers from Nine ASEAN member countries, its two
observer nations and 10 dialogue partners participated in the
forum and discussed a wide range of issues concerning peace and
security in the region.
</P>
<P>
The ministers urged that the evolutionary approach to the
development of the ARF process and the practice of taking
decisions by consensus be maintained, taking into consideration
the interests of all ARF participants, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed concern over the latest development of the
situation in Cambodia. The Malaysian minister told a news briefing
after the meeting that ASEAN will help Cambodia, but only with
permission from the Cambodian government. Phnom Penh had rejected
any help from ASEAN at an earlier time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
