<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changing East China From Desert Into Oasis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A large sandy area in east
China's Jiangxi province has been turned into an oasis after 17
years of sand control work and development.
</P>
<P>
The results have attracted the attention from outside China and
have been praised as an example of sand control projects suitable
for subtropical areas.
</P>
<P>
Gangshang Township, which is 32 kilometers from the city of
Nanchang, used to have a lot of sandy land, because of a changing
river course. In the summer, temperatures there could reach 70
degrees centigrade, and in winter, the sky was usually covered
with sand. A sandbar moved southward at a rate of five meters
annually, wiping out farmland, blocking roads, and destroying
water facilities. In Zoujia Village, 35 of the 36 families were
forced to move out and leave their homes.
</P>
<P>
Desertification also brought poverty with it. In Gangshang, per
capita income was only 89.54 yuan in 1980.
</P>
<P>
But, since the early 1980's, a large number of trees have been
planted in Gangshang to stop the spreading sand, and at the same
time forestry products have become a new resource for local
farmers.
</P>
<P>
As a result, their incomes reached 2,053 yuan in 1996, more
than the provincial average.
</P>
<P>
Seeing the great changes that have occurred, many farmers who
had to leave their hometown in search of a better life, have
decided to move back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Form Task Force for Marine Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran plans to form a special task
force to protect Persian Gulf's marine environment, Vice-
President Hadi Manafi said here today.
</P>
<P>
Manafi, also head of Iran's Environmental Protection Agency,
said that the task force would cooperate with regional countries
in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the official news agency IRNA as saying
that Iran wants to form a regional organization for the
protection of marine environment in cooperation with Gulf
countries and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian vice-president cited the relatively low depth as
well as the existence of a large number of coral islands among
reasons which make Persian Gulf suitable for farming of various
fish.
</P>
<P>
"Several marine species including the sea turtles, dolphins
and sharks are among the protected species recognized by the
Convention on International Trade on Endangered Species, and the
Convention on Bio-Diversity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Voicing concern over high levels of pollution in the Persian
Gulf, Manafi pointed to the navigation of oil tankers in the
regional waters as well as the presence of many foreign military
carriers as threats to the region's fragile marine environment.
</P>
<P>
Manafi specifically pointed to the active presence of large
fleets of U.S. military carriers and their frequent military
maneuvers as major detriments to the efforts to save the
environment in the Persian Gulf. 
</P>
</TEXT>
