<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Resumed in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Guerrillas of the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, or Party of God, today carried out a series of attacks
on positions of the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army (SLA)
militia in the so-called "security zone", claiming that casualties
were caused.
</P>
<P>
Voice of the South radio, organ of the SLA militia, confirmed
that its positions in Jarmaq, Thoura and Bir Kalab were attacked
by Hezbollah guerrillas, and stressed that no militiamen were
killed or wounded.
</P>
<P>
It said that several mortar shells hit vicinities of the town
of Rihan in Jezzine, causing damages.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong SLA militia was armed and trained by Israel to
police the 15-kilometer-wide buffer zone, established by the
Jewish state in 1985 ostensibly to protect northern Israel from
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Resistance, the military wing of Hezbollah,
announced that its fighters also carried out attacks on the
Israeli positions of Ar-Rasha and Jebel Hommeid in the pre-dawn
darkness, using rocket-propelled-grenades and machineguns.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli army spokesman admitted that Lebanese guerrillas
fired Katyusha rockets at the Israeli position of Kawkaba
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Israeli occupation forces resumed bombardment in south Lebanon
this morning and fired artilleries at Iglim Al-Toffah, or
Province of Apple, a ridge often used by Lebanese Muslim
guerrillas as a springboard to launch attacks on the Israeli
self-carved border strip.
</P>
<P>
Israeli gunboats cruising off south Lebanon's Mediterranean
coast opened fire at Lebanese fishing boats without causing
casualties.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes flied reconnaissance missions over the areas
of Iglim Al-Toffah and Nabatiyeh this morning, and broke sound
barrier over the Shiite-populated Baalbek City in eastern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the state-run Lebanon Radio quoted
senior official sources in the Foreign Ministry as saying that the
ministry is preparing to file a complaint with a five-nation
committee overseeing the implementation of a cease-fire in south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In the complaint, the sources said, the Foreign Ministry will
accuse Israeli occupation forces in south Lebanon of violating the
cease-fire understanding, which Lebanon and Israel reached in
April, 1996, by bombarding south Lebanese villagers Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A 60-year-old woman was wounded in the bombardment when a
shell hit her house in the village of Suhmour in Western
Beqaa. The bombardment came in a retaliation for Katyusha attacks
by Hezbollah guerrillas on Israeli positions in the border strip.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire monitoring committee, comprising representatives
from France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States, have
held 14 meetings since this year to look into complaints lodged by
Lebanon and Israel against each other over alleged violations of
the so-called "April understanding."
</P>
<P>
But the committee refrained from making a single condemnation
against either country, a fact which has evoked doubts among
many Lebanese over the effectiveness of the international panel.
</P>
<P>
Mediated by the United States and France, the understanding
barres fighting sides in south Lebanon from targeting civilians
or launching military operations from civilian areas.
</P>
<P>
The Shiite fundamentalist, which seeks to establish an Islamic
republic in Lebanon, spearheads a guerrilla warfare on the last
active battlefront of the Arab-Israeli conflict, to oust Israeli
occupation forces out of the Lebanese land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
