<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Township Enterprises Key to Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- China's township enterprises,
which were developed by farmers, have maintained an annual growth
of more than 20 percent over the past two decades, since China
adopted its reform and opening-up policy in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
The sector had a GDP of 1.76 trillion yuan during the same
period, accounting for 26 percent of the country's GDP. It also
had a value-added industrial output of 1.26 trillion yuan, or 44.2
percent of the nation's total, according to the latest edition of
Beijing's China Economic Herald.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises were the brainchild of farmers, and as a
form of repayment, have provided large amounts of money for
agriculture. From 1991 to 1995, township enterprises spent more
than 100 billion yuan on agriculture.
</P>
<P>
They were also employing 135 million rural laborers by the end
of last year, accounting for 29.4 percent of China's total rural
labor force. In addition, farmers get a third of their income from
the sector.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises have purchased more than six percent of
the country's patent technology, and science and high-tech
companies have contributed 40 percent to the sector's growth. In
the process, some 5,000 township enterprises have become
medium-sized or large enterprises. This has also helped China
modernize agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
