<HEADLINE> Ancient Bricks Found In Recently-excavated Chinese Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A 2,100-year-old tomb recently
discovered at a construction site in Huaibei, in China's Anhui
province contained some ancient hollow bricks.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, which was discovered seven meters underground, was
made of eight large hollow bricks. Five of them were reported to
have been seriously damaged during the construction work.
</P>
<P>
The three intact bricks are grey blocks, 78 cm by 33.5 cm by 18
cm, each weighing 25 kg, local archaeologists say, and have
rhomboid designs and three elliptical holes on them.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the city museum say that man-made bricks from that
period, the Western Han (206 BC-24AD) are rare, and that the
discovery will be useful to research on pottery-making techniques
in ancient China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
