<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Government Urged to Settle Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)'s
government has been urged to map out a plan to deal with high
unemployment rate among the UAE nationals.
</P>
<P>
"Employment of UAE nationals will be among the most serious
challenges facing the country," UAE's Minister of Communications
Ahmed Humaid al Tayer said in a press release today.
</P>
<P>
The oil-rich Gulf country has some 2.4 million people. Two
thirds of them are foreigners who account for about 90 percent of
the whole UAE labor force of 1.29 million at present.
</P>
<P>
"Estimates show that there will be nearly 200,000 citizens in
the year 2006 searching for jobs," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, UAE has provided a large number of jobs for its
qualified nationals to ease reliance on foreign labor.
</P>
<P>
But many institutions, particularly those in the private sector
have been reluctant to recruit nationals on the grounds that they
lack experiences, work fewer hours and demand much higher salaries
than the expatriates.
</P>
<P>
According to independent estimates, nationals account for less
than 10 percent of the private workforce.
</P>
<P>
In the banking sector, UAE natives form only 8.8 percent of
nearly 13,000 employees, said Tayer who heads a government
committee overseeing a job nationalization program in the UAE's 47
banks.
</P>
<P>
He urged the government to map out a plan to settle the
problem, especially in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
"There should be a plan to ensure jobs for them (nationals) in
the private sector and I think national and foreign institutions
should shoulder their responsibility in this respect," he said.
</P>
<P>
The UAE's Labor and Social Affairs Ministry said last week it
had drafted laws to force the private sector to employ nationals.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft laws which should be endorsed by the federal
cabinet, special sections would be set up at government labor
offices in the country to supervise the nationalization of jobs in
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Recruitment of non-nationals in the private sector would not
be allowed unless it is proved that there are no jobless UAE
nationals who can do the same work given to non-nationals.
</P>
<P>
The Labor and Social Affairs Ministry will also be authorized
under the drafted laws to cancel the labor permit granted to a
non-national in some cases, including the case where there is a
local worker who is qualified to do that job.
</P>
</TEXT>
