<HEADLINE> South Koreans Take 11 Gold Medals at Pacific Judo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- South Korean Judo players took
another six gold medals at the Pacific Rim Judo Championships
which concluded on Sunday, bringing its total number of gold
medals to 11.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Judo players grabbed three golds, five silvers and
five bronzes in the two-day competitions, followed by China which
took home two golds, two silvers and four bronzes.
</P>
<P>
South Korean woman Kim Hye Suk won a first gold at the
52-kilogram category today, followed by her teammates Lee Eun Hee
at the 56kg, and Hyun Kyung Lee at the open's category.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Park Yong Gyun won the top title at the men's 60kg
category, and his teammates Kim Jong Won and Kim Joon Hwan also
won at the 65kg and 71kg respectively.
</P>
<P>
Two other gold medals were awarded to China's Li Lingling at
the women's 48kg category, and Japan's Katsuyuki Masuchi at the
men's open category, separately.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei players won two silver medals at the men's 60kg
and 65kg respectively, while Hsiao Hung Lee won another silver at
the women's open category. It won three silver and eight bronze
medals in all.
</P>
<P>
The Australian team missed the gold but did take home five
silver and six bronze medals. the New Zealand team bagged two
bronzes while the United States, Fiji, China's Hong Kong and the
Philippines each took a bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
Listed as world class A Judo competitions, the annual Pacific
Rim Judo Championships attracted more than 160 players from 13
countries and regions this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
