<HEADLINE> Shanghai Fighting Oil Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Customs officials in Shanghai,
one of the key ports for overseas petroleum products entering
China, has developed tough measures to combat the city's rampant
smuggling of petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
According to the Customs Office, the smuggling has been on the
increase since the price of finished oil products dropped in the
world market recently.
</P>
<P>
China became a major importer of oil several years ago and buys
a large amount every year on the world market to meet the growing
domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Customs officers nationwide have seized 62,000 tons of smuggled
oil, valued at 133 million yuan, since the beginning of the year,
and they say they will increase import and export inspections for
finished oil products in the city. They will also join forces with
the police to fight the problem on the sea.
</P>
<P>
China imported 1.14 million tons of oil via Shanghai in the
first half of the year, more than twice the amount for the same
period last year. The total value of imported oil products
imported was 210 million US dollars. Most of it was diesel fuel
for automobiles.  
</P>
</TEXT>
