<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho's Parties Argue on Incorporation with S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The ruling Lesotho Congress
of Democracy (LCD) and major Opposition parties in Lesotho have
been arguing about incorporation with neighboring South Africa,
local daily City Press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of Opposition parties believed that it would be in the
long-term interests of Lesotho to be integrated into South Africa
although it is not something that can be done overnight, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The main Opposition parties, including the Basotho Congress
Party (BCP), Basotho National Party (BNP), Marematlou Freedom
Party (MFP) and the smaller Communist Party of Lesotho (CPL),
have appealed to a national debate over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the former ruling BNP Evaristus Sekhnyana was quoted
as saying that Lesotho should either integrate completely with
South Africa, or, considering the sensitivity of the issue in the
country, it should form a Commonwealth with its neighbor.
</P>
<P>
Senior MFP official Vincent Malebo, who supports
incorporation, said a starting point toward integration could be
the opening of borders between Lesotho and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"It's very difficult for people to forego their sovereignty.
What needs to be done as a starting point is to consider opening
the borders and allow for free flow of people between the two
countries... as the case before South Africa's National party
came to power," he said.
</P>
<P>
BCP Chairman Tseliso Makhakhe said although incorporation was
in their election manifesto, it was a matter that must be
approached with great caution.
</P>
<P>
"It is an emotive issue and needs to be discussed thoroughly
before any decision is taken," he said.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the CPL Mokhafisi Kena said he favors
incorporation, but only after a national debate, the report said.
</P>
<P>
However, the ruling LCD has poured cold water on the idea of
incorporation, noting that the immediate problem facing Lesotho
is not the issue of incorporation, but to formalize its economic
links with South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Tom Thabane, special adviser to Prime Minister Ntsu Mokhehle,
said if economic ties between the two "are formalized and
strengthened", this could be of greater benefit to Lesotho.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
