<HEADLINE> UNHCR Provides Assistance to Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) has given Nepal some 13.27 million
rupees (about 230,000 U.S. dollars) in the past four years for
medical care in its eight refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
Under its program for refugee-affected areas, the UNHCR
provided to the Mechi Zonal Hospital 953,000 rupees (about 16,720
dollars) in 1994 for physical facilities and another 1.61 million
rupees (28,000 dollars) in 1995 for other necessities, the
official RSS news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under its annual program, the UNHCR has set aside for Nepal
about 5.56 million rupees (97,000 dollars) in the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
During this three years, the organization also offered Nepal a
total of 3.66 million rupees (64,000 dollars) for sub-health
posts, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
Other assistance includes 1.21 million rupees (21,000 dollars)
in 1995 for the construction of a hospital building and 247,628
rupees (about 4,340 dollars) in 1996 for two health posts for
furniture and other materials, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, 100,000 Bhutanese of Nepalese origin were forced to
flee to Nepal, who live now in eight camps in eastern Nepal.
</P>
</TEXT>
