<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Nations at Risk by Cigarette Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Record cigarette sales in
developing nations by multi-national cigarette manufacturers are
wreaking havoc to public health and national economies, according
to "Sunday Standard", a Nairobi-based weekly, today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the World Watch Institute (WWI) as saying
that the rise in the cigarettes sale in the developing nations
has caused enormous social and economic cost.
</P>
<P>
An extensive research by the organization warns that within 25
years, tobacco-induced illness is expected to overtake infectious
diseases as the leading threat to human health worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The WWI notes that developing nations, especial African
states, are worse off as their national budgets are heavily
eroded by the entire cost of cigarette smoking.
</P>
<P>
According to the research, tobacco sometimes absorbs up to 17
percent of household income.
</P>
<P>
In many other developing countries, households with just one
smoker spend more on cigarettes than they do on all their health
care, it adds.
</P>
<P>
The research indicates that smoking has imposed a heavy cost
and burden on society as a whole in terms of medical expenses and
loss of lives.
</P>
<P>
Smokers lose an average of 25 years of life, the research
says, adding that most smokers face a three times higher risk of
dying before the age of 70 than non-smokers.
</P>
<P>
Multi-national cigarette firms often go after hardened smokers
with tobacco blends which have a higher tar and nicotine content
than the same brand has in its home markets.
</P>
<P>
The consequence of marketing such brands in developing nations
increases the risks to smokers' health, the U.S.-based
organization stressed.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco companies in the world are producing 5.5 trillion
cigarettes a year, that is, nearly 1,000 cigarettes for every
man, woman and child on average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PAL Seeks Suspension of Philippine-Singapore Air Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) today
urged the government to postpone its forthcoming air talks with
Singapore, citing deficiencies in the Philippine panel's position
and legal impediments affecting the panel chairman.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Secretary Arturo Enrile of the Department of
Transportation and Communications, PAL President Jose Antonio
Garcia urged the government to "reject any form of open skies with
Singapore," saying "this would be immensely harmful to the
national interests."
</P>
<P>
Garcia said that the Philippine panel still has not set clear
parameters in preparation for the talks scheduled for Tuesday,
despite PAL's plea to the panel to "take a rationalized approach
based on true traffic demand."
</P>
<P>
He also called for the barring of Civil Aeronautics Board
member Victor Limlingan from serving as chairman of the Philippine
panel because of "serious questions that have been raised in
connection with his previous dealings with the Singapore
government."
</P>
<P>
On July 25, PAL filed a criminal complaint against Limlingan
for violation of the anti-graft and corrupt practices act.
</P>
<P>
The airline accused Limlingan of "unilaterally amending a
confidential memorandum of understanding" that was "unfairly
favorable to Singapore carriers and damaging to the Philippine
national carrier."
</P>
<P>
As a result of Limlingan's actions, PAL said, the Philippine
Airlines suffered actual damages amounting to 4.5 million U.S.
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
