<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Pledges to Contribute to ARF Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Union
(EU) today pledged to further contribute to the development of the
ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF).
</P>
<P>
The participation in all ARF activities by the EU enables it
and its member states to bring their experience, means and views
to a regional process that inevitably has implications for global
security and stability, Luxembourg Foreign Minister Jacques F.
Poos said at the ARF meeting here on behalf of the E.U., whose
rotating presidency is now held by Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
The EU will continue to share its knowledge and resources, he
said, adding that it has always been willing to consider needs
that have been brought to its attention.
</P>
<P>
"The EU has made available considerable means in the fields of
humanitarian aid, training, technical and medical assistance in
this region," he said.
</P>
<P>
As the ARF is moving toward a new phase of activity, the EU
would be ready to play an active role in helping prevent or manage
crises, by working closely with the countries of the region and
relevant international bodies, Poos said.
</P>
<P>
He was of the view that participating in the ARF also allows
the EU to learn from this process which he said has made a very
important contribution to the stability and security of the
Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the ARF is still in its early stages, a
high degree of comfort now characterizes interactions between
participants.
</P>
<P>
"It is the ultimate goal of ARF participants to provide
security and most importantly, prosperity for all people in this
region," he said.
</P>
<P>
The participants in the ARF are nine ASEAN members, 10 ASEAN
dialogue partners including the EU and two ASEAN observers.
</P>
</TEXT>
