<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Develops New Anti-Tank Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 27 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli army will be
equipped with a new anti-tank missile known as the Gill, which
more than doubles the range of the outdated U.S.-supplied Dragon
missiles, reported the pro-government newspaper The Jerusalem
Post today.
</P>
<P>
The missile, also called the Small Spike, was developed and
built by the Armaments Development Authority (Rafael) and has
entered low-rate production after meeting the operational
requirements of the army.
</P>
<P>
The anti-armor missile has a range of up to 2.5 kilometers,
which protects the operator and launch platform from
counter-measures. The Gill is simple to operate and can be used in
bad weather, according to Rafael.
</P>
<P>
It will replace the Dragon, which has a range of about 1,000
meters. The Gill is a "fire-and-forget" missile designed to kill
any target on the battlefield, including main battle tanks and
hovering helicopters.
</P>
<P>
The Israel-made new anti-tank missile has been offered to
Netherlands and the U.S.. Its nearest competitor is the Javelin,
built by Texas Instruments/Lockheed Martin, which last month won
a 745 million U.S. dollars contract to supply the U.S. army.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the stalemate in the Middle East peace process,
the Israeli Defense Ministry and the army have made increasing
efforts to strengthen preparedness for war.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has called on the government
to have an increase of 450 million dollars for the 1998 defense
budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
