<HEADLINE> Cambodia Still Wants to Join ASEAN: Ung Huot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia today
once again expressed its desire to join the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and said it would accept ASEAN
mediation in settling the conflict in the country.
</P>
<P>
"The Kingdom of Cambodia remains unchanged in its firm
determination to become member of the ASEAN as soon as possible,"
Cambodian Foreign Minister Ung Huot told the Fourth ASEAN Regional
Forum meeting, which opened here this morning.
</P>
<P>
The minister also declared that Cambodia "warmly welcomes the
role of the ASEAN to help restore political stability" in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia was supposed to join the ASEAN together with Laos and
Myanmar at the 30th ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM) held here last
Wednesday, but its admission has been deferred because of fighting
between forces of Co-Prime Ministers of Norodom Ranariddh and Hun
Sen.
</P>
<P>
Earlier effort by the ASEAN to negotiate between the Cambodian
parties was rejected by Hun Sen, who said the fighting, which
resulted in the ouster of First Prime Minister Ranariddh, was
Cambodia's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The change of position was first indicated during the AMM held
here on July 24 and 25 by Ung Huot, who said his country would
accept an ASEAN role in helping bring stability to his country.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign ministers of the nine ASEAN member
countries said in a joint communique at the end of their meeting
that the ASEAN would continue its effort only upon reconfirmation
of the new Cambodian position.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot promised that the Cambodian government is to normalize
the situation and maintain political stability in the country and
continue its efforts to make Cambodia a real state governed by the
rules of law.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged that the Cambodian Constitution and the system
of constitutional monarchy with Norodom Sihanouk as the country's
sovereign will remain unchanged and the state institutions of the
royal government of Cambodia will be maintained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
