<HEADLINE> Kazak Herdsmen in China Finding Cotton Better Than Wool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A growing number of Kazak herdsmen
in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in China's northwest are
finding that growing cotton is more profitable than tending sheep.
</P>
<P>
During spring planting, a machine was spreading plastic
sheeting on cotton fields of Xigebi Village in Manasi County,
while Kazak herdsmen worked in the field.
</P>
<P>
"I planted 1.2 ha of cotton last year, earning nearly 20,000
yuan. I plan to plant two ha this year, and expect more than
40,000 yuan in profits," said Yejinbek, a Kazak villager.
</P>
<P>
Back in 1992, however, when eight Kazak families planted about
3.5 ha of cotton for the first time, they got next to nothing
because of their ignorance of farming methods.
</P>
<P>
"We got so excited when the cotton was about to blossom. We
waited in the fields for several days, but no cotton came out. So
we just broke off the bolls and took out the cotton, which nobody
bought," Yejinbek recalled.
</P>
<P>
The next year, people were afraid to grow cotton.
</P>
<P>
Then, in 1994, two technicians were sent to the village, and
the herdsmen earned 700 yuan per capita growing cotton that
year. The herdsmen had more than 4,000 yuan of per capita income
last year, compared to 420 yuan in 1990. This year, 100 ha of
cotton were planted, which are expected to put 2,700 yuan in each
villager's pocket. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
