<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Express Mail Service Developing in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- In only a few years' time, the
Express Mail Service (EMS) in Tianjin, east of Beijing, has done
very well.
</P>
<P>
In the January-May period of this year, there were more than
5.8 million pieces posted through EMS, registering a 70 percent
increase from the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
More than 40 post offices in Tianjin handle about 5,000 pieces
of EMS mail daily.
</P>
<P>
Major destinations of this mail range from Beijing, Shanghai,
Guangzhou, Nanjing, and Hong Kong to Japan, the Republic of Korea
and the US.
</P>
<P>
To increase the service, Tianjin EMS opened 185 special
services at the beginning of the year to give advice, answer
inquiries, take complaints, and settle damage claims.
</P>
<P>
Individual mail is occupying a smaller share of the mail
handled, as businesses and government offices now make up 85
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
