<HEADLINE> Thai Economy to Destabilise Government: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 27 (Xinhua) -- A failure to tackle economic
problems, rather than political infighting among coalition
partners, is the factor most likely to de stabilize the
government, said a Chart Pattana Party leader.
</P>
<P>
The government's stability depends on the country's economic
situation. I the situation does not improve, the government's
stability will become critical, the Bangkok Post today quotes
Suwat Liptapallop, general secretary of Chart Pattana Party, as
saying. Suwat is also minister of transport and communications.
</P>
<P>
Chart Pattana Party is the second largest partner in the
six-party coalition government headed by Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Professor Krirk-kiat Pipatserithem, a former member
of the country's planning agency, the National Economic and Social
Development Board, said, "The economic situation is now at its
most critical stage.' He doubted the present government could
tackle the problems because the public had lost confidence in it.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will not be able to maintain the
currency at 30 baht a dollar, as was expected and acceptable, and
it is now falling to 32 baht, losing 24 percent of its value
against the dollar since its flotation on July 2.
</P>
<P>
He is of the view that if the situation worsens, the common
people will be affected with the inflation climbing and essential
commodity prices rising.  
</P>
</TEXT>
