<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Blames "El Nino" for Forest Fires, Declares Alerts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Colombia blamed the "El
Nino" phenomenon for recent forest fires and declared yellow and
orange alerts in its Caribbean and the Andean regions this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The early arrival of the warm ocean currents has caused average
temperatures to rise to 40 degrees Celsius in several departments,
such as Guajira, Cesar and Cordoba, the Environment Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The temperatures were above historical highs and have led to
more forest fires, explained the Office of Environmental Alerts of
the Institute of Hydrology, Meteorology and Environmental Studies.
</P>
<P>
In July alone, said the Environment Ministry, 616 forest fires
affecting were reported in several departments.
</P>
<P>
While 561 forest fires were reported from December 1996 to
March 1997, more than 700 similar fires were on the official
record from June to September of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, said a ministry report, the "El Nino" not only will
intensify the present drought, but also will make it more acute at
the end of 1997 and in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
The ministry called on governors, mayors, directors of
autonomous regions and natural parks, and other local authorities
to adopt measures to prevent forest fires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
