<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Urges ARF to Focus on Regional Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PETALING JAYA, Malaysia, July 27 (Xinhua) -- China today called
on the ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF) to focus on regional peace and
security and base the participants' relationship on principles of
respect for sovereignty and non-interference in one another's
internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The ARF "should take the maintenance of regional peace and
security as its objective, living together in peace and treating
each other as equals as its purpose, confidence-building as its
core task and dialogues and cooperation as means to achieve the
objective," Chinese Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen
told the Fourth ARF, which opened here this morning.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the meeting of the 21 ARF participants is "not to
defuse a common threat, but rather to achieve a common goal, that
is, regional peace and stability."
</P>
<P>
The ARF participants include the nine ASEAN member countries --
Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam, the two observer countries
Cambodia and Papua New Guinea, and the 10 dialogue partners --
Australia, Canada, China, India, Japan, New Zealand, Russia, South
Korea, the United States and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice premier stressed, "It is important to observe
the principles of respect for sovereignty and non-interference in
each other's internal affairs in the activities of the ARF and
make effort to expand common ground beyond differences, increase
confidence and accommodate the security concerns of all parties."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that a friendly and stable state-to-state
relationship based on equality is an important political
foundation for peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, sustained economic development and constantly
expanded economic exchanges and cooperation among countries may
increase interdependence of their interests and thus provide a
firm economic basis for regional security, Qian stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also described dialogues and cooperation as "major pillars
for regional peace and development" and the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) and the ARF as "multilateral efforts based on
dialogues and cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Qian called for resolving disputes through peaceful means,
saying it is "a proper way" to safeguard regional peace and
stability.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that as an Asian-Pacific country and a permanent
member of the U.N. Security Council, China attaches great
importance to the maintenance of peace and stability in the region
and has made its contributions to it.
</P>
<P>
China's stability and prosperity constitute a strong support
for regional peace and prosperity, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that China pursues an independent foreign policy of
peace, seeks neither alliance nor confrontation and lives in amity
and good-neighborliness with other countries in the region and
treats them as equals.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed China's readiness to settle disputes between
states through peaceful means, saying it has tried to increase
mutual confidence and resolve issues with other countries "through
sincere and candid dialogues and consultations."
</P>
<P>
He cited as examples the negotiated settlement of the question
of Hong Kong, over which China resumed exercise of sovereignty on
July 1 this year, and that of Macao which will return to China in
two years.
</P>
<P>
Qian described China's resumption of the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong as "a major event that has attracted
worldwide attention."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's return has further strengthened the links between
China on the one hand and Asia and the world at large on the other
and will further promote peace and prosperity in the Asia-Pacific
region," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
While noting the good developments in the region, Qian also
drew attention to what he called "the destabilizing factors."
</P>
<P>
"The eruption of armed conflict in Cambodia is a matter of
concern," he said. "Some newly-emerging trans-national issues are
posing new challenges."
</P>
<P>
He called for proper handling of these problems in order to
prevent them from adversely affecting peace and stability in the
region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
