<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shifting Food and Clothing Patterns for Chinese Ethnic Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Edible wild plants that local
people once thought were only the very last resort during a period
of famine, are now making their debut on the menus of many
restaurants in Hohhot, the capital of north China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Many of the elderly can still remember when, in 1929, the city
was hit by the worst flood it had ever seen, and the fields were
left barren, and most of them had only wild plants, grass, and
bark to survive on.
</P>
<P>
Now, to their surprise, these very same plants, not worth
looking at when they had enough to eat in the past, are appearing
in the marketplace in nice packaging.
</P>
<P>
According to one survey, in 1996, the per capita consumption of
meat, eggs, and milk exceeded 30 kg in Hohhot, quite a bit more
than a decade ago, and one merchant explains, "Since people eat
fish and meat everyday, they want to have a change."
</P>
<P>
Per capita income in Hohhot was 3,500 yuan (about 440 US
dollars) in 1996, four times the figure of a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
And the increasing amount of money has brought a change in
clothing tastes for Hohhot's 670,000 people, who belong to 36
national minorities like Mongolian, Hui, Daur, and Oroqen.
</P>
<P>
"The traditional Mongolian robe is not convenient to wear in
the city," Su Rina, a Mongolian girl explained to the reporter
while she was trying on a white silk dress in a boutique. Standing
nearby was a slender girl dressed in black jacket and trousers, a
quite appealing figure to the passersby. "But during festivals, I
still prefer the Mongolian robe," Su added.
</P>
<P>
The beautiful clothing of the young people has naturally caused
the elderly to recall the past. "At their age, I could only wear
the clothes my mother made from her old ones, full of patches,"
said 68-year-old Zhao Shuying, a retired worker and member of the
Daur.
</P>
<P>
But even though she was talking in this way, she was also
fairly well dressed in a white jacket and brown trousers.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 16 percent of people's living expenses in Hohhot
went for clothes, statistics tell us. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Province to Become China's New Granary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi Province
set a record high in its summer grain production this year by 5.53
billion kg, an increase of 1.18 billion kg, which accounted for a
quarter of the country's summer grain increases.
</P>
<P>
This largest increase in China is the result of Shaanxi's
efforts to become a major grain producer and balance grain
supplies in the western parts of the country -- as required by the
state, according to the provincial Agriculture Department.
</P>
<P>
Increased investment contributed greatly to agricultural
development. The province spent 1.68 billion yuan on agriculture
from last year to the end of this May, a year-on-year increase of
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Widespread application of advanced farming techniques also
played a role in the development. Shaanxi has cultivated and
provided 35 percent of the seeds, and applied high technology to
84 percent of its maize acreage.
</P>
<P>
The province spent 1.5 billion yuan on improving water
conservancy facilities last year, and its 30 percent of irrigated
growing area produced more than 70 percent of the total grain
output.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi also is working to help 100 selected
agriculture-related enterprises increase values of farm produce,
in a move to promote grain production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
