<HEADLINE> 244 Pieces of Firearms Destroyed in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 26 (Xinhua) -- To take illegal weapons off
the streets, 244 pieces of firearms were destroyed today in a
neighborhood outside Panama City, said the Mayor's Office.
</P>
<P>
The weapons collected at the San Joaquin Parish in the El
Pedregal neighborhood, some 50 kilometers west of this capital,
were exchanged for food stamps worth 30,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The event was part of the third phase of the "No To Weapons,
Yes To Peace" program initiated by Panama City Mayor Mayin Correa
and financed by the representatives of a private company.
</P>
<P>
It was also supported by government institutions, the National
Police, the Catholic Church, civic groups and communities involved.
</P>
<P>
Organizers paid a total of 120,000 dollars during the
weapon-for-food exchange, which started on June 26 and ended on
July 15, to take the firearms off the streets and away from homes.
</P>
<P>
Previous activities of the program were carried out in the
three urban neighborhoods of El Chorrillo, Curundu and San
Joaquin, where high crime rates had been recorded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
