<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Down on Oil Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Customs has stepped up its
efforts to fight an increasing amount of smuggling of refined oil.
</P>
<P>
Chinese customs stopped 41 attempts to smuggle refined oil into
the country over the first half of this year. Some 62,000 metric
tons of refined oil worth 133 million yuan (about 16 million US
dollars) was seized, today's Business Weekly (China Daily) quoted
a report from the General Administration of Customs as saying.
</P>
<P>
The nosedive of oil prices in the international market starting
in March added to the rampage of illegal trafficking of finished
oil to China, said a customs official.
</P>
<P>
The average price of oil in the international market is 17 US
dollars per barrel, about half of the price in the Chinese
market. The big gap prompted traffickers to smuggle oil to the
country.
</P>
<P>
Most of the smuggling was by water, according to another
customs official. South China's Guangdong province, Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region and east China's Zhejiang province initiated
battles against oil smuggling and strengthened inspection on the
sea between late May and June.
</P>
<P>
In March alone, Guangzhou Customs ferreted out six smuggling
cases and seized 7,000 metric tons of diesel worth 14 million yuan
(about 1.69 million US dollars).
</P>
<P>
On June 29, Zhanjiang Customs of Guangdong province found a
boat plying the seas between the mainland and Hong Kong and Macao,
and carrying 1,000 tons of diesel, which was valued at two million
yuan (about 241,000 US dollars). 
</P>
