<HEADLINE> Ukraine Begins to Form New Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Lenonid Kuchma
today started to name a new cabinet, with most of the 75 former
cabinet members are expected to stay.
</P>
<P>
Economy Minister Viktor Suslov, Energy Minister Alexey
Sheberstov and Minister of Coal Industry Stanislav Yanko are three
new faces among the 21 already appointed ministers.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko, who came into office on
July 16 after his predecessor Pavel Lazarenko resigned, said
Foreign Minister Gennady Udovenko would also remain in his post.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko vowed to reform the cabinet and improve its
efficiency and enhance cooperation among the 75 ministries.
</P>
<P>
The new cabinet faces three major tasks, the prime minister
noted, namely to develop the national economy, improve the
environment and stimulate the production by state-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
All of Pustovoitenko's six predecessors had failed to bring
Ukraine out from the downward economic spiral since the former
Soviet republic's gained independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian economy dropped by 7.5 percent in the first half
of 1997 following a 10-percent decline in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
