<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coastal Province Speeding up Chemical Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Shandong, a coastal province in
north China, has vowed to build up a comprehensive chemical
industrial system and open the sector further to international
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Years of construction have laid a solid foundation for the
further development of the chemical industry," said Pei Xiutang,
director of Shandong's provincial department of oil and chemical
industries.
</P>
<P>
Shandong is now able to produce more than 2,000 kinds of
chemicals with 20,000 varieties, of which the output of synthetic
ammonia, fertilizer, soda ash, caustic soda and tires are among
the top three in Chinese provinces, according to Pei.
</P>
<P>
The chemical system annually puts 100-plus new products into
actual production, Pei added.
</P>
<P>
Shandong plans to register an annual turnover of 40 billion
yuan in chemical products before the new century. Its chemical
sector is also expected to earn one billion US dollars in foreign
exchange and use one billion US dollars of overseas investment by
2000, Pei said.
</P>
<P>
"The province in the remaining years of the century will focus
on the development of agricultural chemicals, rubber processing,
petrochemicals and fine chemicals, and foster eighty large
chemical enterprises and chemical groups," Pei said.
</P>
<P>
The province last year posted a chemical industrial turnover of
28 billion yuan and its chemical sales reached 31.9 billion yuan,
both of which ranked first among China's provincial
administrations.
</P>
<P>
Some 120 joint ventures have registered in the province, with a
combined investment of 300 million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
