<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Can Avoid Currency Crisis Southeast Asia Suffers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- China, enjoying a table economic
situation and favorable balance of international payment, could
build on its rich foreign exchange reserves, good overseas capital
inflows structure and effective management to hedge against the
kind of currency upheaval that hit Southeast Asia recently.
</P>
<P>
The sharp devaluation of currencies in Southeast Asian
countries mainly resulted from the sudden withdrawal of foreign
capital and the selling of local currencies by international
speculators when these countries suffered expanding deficits in
current accounts, declining exports and slower economic growth,
which has weakened overseas investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
"But the situation in China is completely different," Chen
Quangeng, a foreign exchange expert, was quoted by today's
Business Weekly (China Daily) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Chen said that most of the foreign capital that has flowed into
China was long-term direct investments under good management. This
part of investment can not be withdrawn suddenly.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign debt is mainly composed of medium- and
long-term loans, meaning foreign fund is stable as its flow back
is limited by the term.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors, who are allowed to trade B shares only in
China, can not enter the bond and A-share markets. Chen believed
that foreign investor's trading will not affect China's foreign
exchange resource.
</P>
<P>
Besides, China applies strict control over the inflow and
outflow of capital which makes it difficult for foreign
speculators to conduct speculation activities in China, Chen noted.
</P>
<P>
"More importantly, China has a strong economic base, enjoying a
satisfactory macro economic situation," Chen was quoted as saying,
"China's economy has succeeded in a soft landing after adopting a
three-year relatively strict monetary and fiscal policy.
</P>
<P>
"it is impossible that a large amount of funds flows out of
China to trigger a financial crisis and currency devaluation,"
Chen said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970727.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researcher Urges Updating Laws on Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 27 (Xinhua) -- China should update its laws and
regulations regarding foreign investment in China, said Wang
Yungui of the Institute of International Economy, a think-tank for
the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
Interviewed by Beijing-based English paper "China Daily", Wang
said that a new law, which combines laws concerning joint
ventures, cooperative enterprises and solely-funded enterprises,
should be enacted.
</P>
<P>
The move will not only better direct foreign investment but
also stave off foreign investors' complaints about the haziness of
Chinese laws and regulations, the researcher said.
</P>
<P>
Although China's current laws and regulations spell out sectors
where foreign investment is encouraged, allowed, restricted and
prohibited, there are no specific measures to go with them.
</P>
<P>
Wang suggested canceling the category where foreign investment
is encouraged as capital flows always go after profits and can be
barely be influenced by official statements, noting that foreign
investment should not be restricted in unimportant industries such
as beer and cosmetic sectors, but only in pillar industries
crucial to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The researcher emphasized that punitive measures should be
added to ensure the enforcement of restrictive catalogue. The
approval rights of central industry authorities should also be
expanded to guarantee the wholesome development of the whole
industry.
</P>
<P>
Some sectors, like container production, have been put into the
restrictive catalogue for years, but suffered from a glut of
foreign investment as local governments only seek for local
interests.
</P>
<P>
Also included should be the requirements concerning the
share-holding ratio between the Chinese and foreign partners in
different industries, technology transfer and foreign investment
in research and development, Wang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
