<HEADLINE> Floods Affect 8,000 People in Southern Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Heavy rains have soaked southern
Venezuela in the last few days and have affected more than 8,000
people in the state of Apure.
</P>
<P>
The Sarare River, which flows through the cities of Guasdualito
and El Amparo in the Jose Antonio Paez municipality, broke the
dikes in three places.
</P>
<P>
High waters also razed the houses of 1,500 families.
</P>
<P>
Civil defense officials, fire-fighting brigades, the National
Guard, and volunteer groups have been called in to rescue people
still being trapped by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Calling it the worst flooding in Guasdualito in the past few
years, Apure State governor Jose Gregorio Montilla requested the
national government to assist flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Montilla estimated that 700 million to one billion bolivars
(1.46 million to 2.08 million U.S. dollars) would be needed to
rebuild the flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
He added that there is not yet an estimation of casualties and
material losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
