<HEADLINE> Young Couples From China's Ethnic Groups Like Simple Weddings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Group weddings have become a
popular and simple way for young couples to begin their new life
in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, which is
home to various ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
Jarken and Nurguli joined seven other Kazak brides and
bridegrooms recently in one such group wedding ceremony sponsored
by the local government.
</P>
<P>
"It was really an unforgetable experience, exciting,
enthusiastic, tasteful, and above all, it was simple; that is,
something we can afford without financial aid from our parents,"
explained Jarken, with smile still on his face.
</P>
<P>
They walked hand-in-hand into the wedding hall, dressed in
ethnic wedding garments, he recalled, noting that this was the
first group wedding ceremony to be held in their remote hometown
of Shitizi Kazak Ethnic Township, in Hutubi County.
</P>
<P>
On that day, he said, the decorated county government hall was
crowded with local people who came to congratulate the couples.
</P>
<P>
Lu Hengzu, the Hutubi County head, hurried to the wedding some
40 km away to preside over the ceremony. He told Xinhua that
although the life of local herdsmen has been getting better and
better in recent years, extravagant weddings have become a real
burden for the people there.
</P>
<P>
As if to make this point, Ahanjiren, Jarken's 58-year-old
father, said: "I have five sons and one daughter. Since 1990, my
three sons have gotten married one by one, spending tens of
thousands yuan. My fourth son, Jarken, fell in love with Nurguli a
few years ago, but we just couldn't afford such high costs." The
average wedding expenditure can be as high as 60,000 yuan (about
7,500 US dollars), he explained.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to necessary household appliances, jewelry, and
clothing, things like cars, motorcycles, and tractors may also be
added to the list of gifts the bride's family asks for," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Although the Kazak people are getting richer as the result of
an economic boom there, most of them cannot afford such a lavish
wedding, and some are driven into the poorhouse by such weddings,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
According to one local official, extravagant weddings not only
put a burden on the Kazak people but also pollute the simple and
honest folkways.
</P>
<P>
"We advocate simple wedding arrangements, but in an ethnic
way. And we encourage young couples to join group weddings," the
official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
