<HEADLINE> Berger Takes Pole Position in Formula One Comeback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Gerhard Berger took the pole
position for Sunday's German Grand Prix Formula One race for his
comeback to the sport.
</P>
<P>
Berger, who missed the previous three Grand Prix races due to
sinus surgery, drove his Benetton-Renault to the fastest lap in
Saturday's qualifying session.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian, who turns 38 next month and is the oldest driver
still active on the circuit, will be without a team next season as
his two-year contract expires at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
Giancarlo Fisichella of Italy, who will replace Berger at
Benetton-Renault next year, came in second and will share the
front row of the starting grid with Berger.
</P>
<P>
German brothers Michael and Ralf Schumacher, who finished
one-two in the free practice on Friday, failed to put up good
performances in Saturday's qualifying session.
</P>
<P>
Michael Schumacher posted a time of 1:42.181 in his Ferrari to
finish fourth, just behind Mika Hakkinen of Finland who drove a
McLaren-Mercedes for the third place in a time of 1:42.034.
</P>
</TEXT>
