<HEADLINE> Honey, a Source of Income in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, July 27 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in northwest China's
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region have been leading a honeysweet life
as the beekeeping business there booms, bringing in 25 million
yuan (about 3.1 million US dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
"I have nearly 300 colonies of bees," said Long Jiuchou, a
local beekeeper who earned more than 50,000 yuan from his job last
year. "And my life gets better and better," he added.
</P>
<P>
The region has about four billion bees, and a honey output of
more than 5,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
"Ningxia is blessed with more than two million hectares of
plants that are good for making honey," said Zong Guanyun, a
beekeeping expert.
</P>
<P>
To develop the region's honey industry, the state allocated 1.6
million yuan and 2,500 cubic meters of timber in the 1970s to help
local farmers build research centers and apiaries. And an
apiculture association was set up in the region in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
