<HEADLINE> UNSCOM, Iraq Agree on Weapon Elimination Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 26 (Xinhua) -- Richard Butler, new U.N. chief
inspector of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, said here today
he had reached an agreement with Iraqi leaders on work needed to
eliminate those weapons.
</P>
<P>
Concrete results will be achieved within three to four weeks,
he told a press conference this evening before wrapping up a
two-day visit to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The inspectors' team of the U.N. Special Commission on Iraq
(UNSCOM), comprising some 150 experts, is to make sure that Iraq
is no longer possessing chemical and biological weapons or capable
of producing long-range missiles.
</P>
<P>
Butler had spent four and half days since last Monday in
Baghdad where he discussed with deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz
on measures of identifying and eliminating the weapons of mass
destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said that he told Aziz "this process has gone far too long
and must be brought to a conclusion," and that he (Aziz) agreed
that for this purpose, we ought to work with a new spirit and
determination to finish this work."
</P>
<P>
"At the end of our discussions, we reached an agreement on a
program of work for the musts ahead, and agreement on things that
must be done to demonstrate progress with respect to each of those
three baskets of weapons," Butler said.
</P>
<P>
Both his team and the Iraqi side are aware that "the Security
Council has resolved that UNSCOM must give it a special report of
the status of these matters, a report to be presented on October
11, he added.
</P>
<P>
He criticized Iraq for failing to grant "immediate and
unconditional access" to any location deemed necessary by UNSCOM
inspectors, who would certify the total elimination of weapons of
mass destruction in Iraq before U.N. sanctions can be lifted.
</P>
<P>
Butler also urged Baghdad to provide necessary information for
an early determination of the nature and size of those weapon
systems.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council has been opposing any relaxation of its
six-year-old sanctions on Iraq until Baghdad fully complies with
the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of work to be done in the next two months and
the work program agreed upon is only a part of what is to be
done," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said the Security Council decision on UNSCOM mission has two
parts - "one has to do with disarmament and the other future
monitoring."
</P>
<P>
Butler flew in Friday after concluding his visit to Iraq to
detail his policies on Iraq and his talks with Tareq Aziz to
Kuwaiti leaders.
</P>
<P>
"It was natural in my view that we should come straight here to
see, to meet with the leaers of the Kuwaiti government and to ease
their concerns about our work," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
This was his first visit to Kuwait since he took over the post
as chief inspector. He reassured the Kuwaiti leadership on
UNSCOM's unwavered determination to obtain Iraq's compliance with
U.N. resolutions related to its aggression on the small, oil-rich
emirate in 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
He held talks with Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah,
acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmad
Al-Jaber Al-Sabah and Defense Minister Sheikh Salem Sabah Al-Salem.
</P>
<P>
Butler would leave Kuwait for Bahrain tomorrow morning before
going to New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
